<p>Cha b‚Äôurrain dhomh a‚Äô bhith air freagairt na b‚Äôfhe√†rr fhaighinn do mo ceistean ‚Äî no sin mo bheachd fh√¨n co-dhiu. Chan eil fhios ‚Äôam fhathast am bidh p√†ipearan ri‚Äôm faighinn bho l√†ithean tr√†th na h-eaglaise. Ma bhios, bidh cothrom agamsa G√†idhlig a leughadh a bha air a sgriobhadh le mo shinnsearan fh√¨n ‚Äî sinnsearan a bh‚Äôanns na St√†itean Aonaichte ron √†m a bha a leithid ann. Ann an doigh, bha iadsan cuideachd ann an √†ite nach robh na √†ite ‚Äî fhathast.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>[Mar as √†bhaist, cha cuiridh mi stuth d√†-chananach na mo bhl√≤g G√†idhlig, ach tha an d√† thionndadh agam mar tha, agus is docha gum bitheadh an tionndadh ‚Äôsa Bheurla cuideachail do fheudhainn.]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>In a Place That‚Äôs Not a Place </strong></p>
<p>by Rudy Ramsey</p>
<p>I‚Äôve done many things in my life that I found exciting ‚Äî things like sports-car racing, aerobatics, marathons, taekwon-do. Which events were the most exciting? Well, often, they weren‚Äôt these things at all, but quiet days when I discovered new pieces of interesting information about my ancestors. Now that‚Äôs exciting! I‚Äôll tell you about a day like that. It‚Äôs a true story about my own ancestors and the language of the Gaels.</p>
<p>I had questions on this subject for more than twenty years. At long last, I found the answers. And here‚Äôs a riddle for you. I found the answers when I was in a place that‚Äôs not a place, in a time that‚Äôs not our own. Where was I?</p>
<p>I‚Äôm a genealogist ‚Äî a family historian, really.¬† I have a lot of ancestors who immigrated from Scotland to Northern Ireland, lived there for a generation, and then emigrated to North Carolina. It‚Äôs a common pattern, known as ‚ÄúUlster Scots‚Äù. I have perhaps 15 surnames in my ancestral tree with this immigration pattern.</p>
<p>There‚Äôs one family like this which has a special interest for me, with the surname ‚ÄúKeahey‚Äù these days, or ‚ÄúMacKeachey‚Äù or ‚ÄúMacGeachie‚Äù in the old country long ago. They emigrated from Scotland to Northern Ireland before 1749. I know this because their three sons were born in Northern Ireland in that year, or the three or four years thereafter. I suspect that they left Scotland after the Jacobite Rebellion, but I‚Äôm not yet certain.</p>
<p>They came to North Carolina, reportedly in 1767, but in any case before the American Revolution. They lived nearly 50 years in a Scottish part of North Carolina. I always wondered whether they were G√†idhlig speakers, and if they were, I wondered how long they retained the language in America. But I didn‚Äôt think I would ever find such information.</p>
<p>My interest in these questions increased after I started learning G√†idhlig myself, for reasons unrelated to family history. Even so, I didn‚Äôt find the answers quickly.</p>
<p>But there came, at long last, a very special day. I was in a place that‚Äôs not a place, in a time that‚Äôs not our own. Well, I was on the internet, anyway ‚Äî a thing that‚Äôs everywhere and nowhere at all. And I was in a time far, far away from the present. I was reading the history of an old church that was in Mississippi long ago. And there they were ‚Äî my ancestors and my answers.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs the history. In the year 1816, the three sons emigrated from North Carolina to Mississippi. This wasn‚Äôt possible for them before then, because their father‚Äôs health was too poor for such a trip. But their father died, and after a short while, the whole family left to seek their fortune in the new state. The sons were old men by then. They themselves had never lived in Scotland; they had spent nearly half a century in this country; would there have been any trace of G√†idhlig still with them?<br />
Well, as it happened, they formed a new church in Mississippi ‚Äî a church called the Philadelphus Presbyterian Church, the name of an old church in North Carolina, where they had lived. According to the history of the new church, it was created in the house of one of my ancestors. And eight of the eleven founding members were my own ancestors.</p>
<p>But here‚Äôs the most important thing to me: Scottish Gaelic was used in the founders‚Äô meetings. The minutes of the meetings were written in G√†idhlig. They built a new school, too, after a year or two. And there, in Wayne County, in Mississippi, in the true deep south of the United States, every class was taught in the language of the Gaels. And that remained true for several years, until new people came to the area who spoke no G√†idhlig at all.</p>
<p>A better answer to my questions would not be possible ‚Äî or that‚Äôs my opinion, anyway. I don‚Äôt know yet whether there are papers still surviving from the early days of the church. If so, I‚Äôll have an opportunity to read G√†idhlig written by my own ancestors ‚Äî ancestors who were in the United States before there was such a place. In a way, they, too, were in a place that wasn‚Äôt a place ‚Äî yet.</p>
